      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "3f12709d3cb75a30",
        "text": "The concept of organization only gained clearer contours in the second half of the 19th century. In the Middle Ages, a special term for what we now call organizations had been unnecessary. Nor would it have had any object, for social order was guaranteed by the stratification of family households and by corporations and, moreover, was subject to a variety of legal regulations. It was not until the course of the 19th century that a usage of language was consolidated that distinguished organizations as social formations of a special kind from other social orders (for example, from communities or from social classes). Only since then has the term organization also been used in normal everyday and scientific language to designate an object of a special kind. Already often used in the 18th century, it initially denotes the order of organic life as distinct from artifacts and mechanisms.2 Jean Paul still considers the application of the term organization to non-organic facts to be a metaphorical use of language, but he himself also speaks of the organization of texts, in the sense of an active-ordering production. Perhaps, then, the transition to an active, activity-related use of the word is the process that generalizes the term. In any case, the term organization has at first a cosmological breadth and remains related to the \"organic\" scheme of the whole and its parts, but offers the possibility to designate at the same time an activity and its effect without getting involved in this difference."
